<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike traditional Champagne, prosecco's fresh, fruit-forward character makes it primarily a wine for immediate enjoyment, though different quality levels offer varying aging potential that reflects their production methods and terroir.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Quality Level</h3>

<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> should be consumed within 1-2 years of purchase. The tank method (Charmat) preserves primary fruit flavors—green apple, pear, and citrus—that begin to fade after this window. <strong>Prosecco DOCG</strong> from Conegliano Valdobbiadene, with its superior terroir and stricter regulations, can maintain quality for 2-3 years, developing subtle honey and brioche notes.</p>

<p><strong>Prosecco Superiore DOCG</strong> and <strong>Cartizze</strong> represent the pinnacle, potentially improving for 3-5 years. These wines from steep hillside vineyards develop greater complexity, with the acidity softening and mineral notes becoming more pronounced.</p>

<h3>Evolution and Peak Windows</h3>

<p>Unlike wines that develop through tannin integration, prosecco evolves through the interaction of its natural acidity with residual yeasts and subtle oxidation. Fresh releases showcase vibrant fruit and floral aromatics, while aged prosecco develops nutty, almond-like characteristics and a creamier mousse texture.</p>

<p>Peak drinking windows: DOC (within 18 months), DOCG (18 months to 2.5 years), and premium Cartizze (2-4 years after harvest).</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>

<p>Store bottles horizontally in a cool, dark environment at 50-55°F with 70% humidity. Prosecco's delicate bubbles and fresh character make it particularly sensitive to temperature fluctuations and light exposure, which can cause premature oxidation and loss of effervescence.</p>

<p>Signs of proper aging include subtle golden color development and integrated flavors, while spoilage appears as flat bubbles, overly brown color, or nutty oxidation that overwhelms fruit character.</p>

